 provides and how that resonates with the structure of relationships between men and women today. Fifty Shades, Illouz argues, is a gothic romance adapted to modern times in which sexuality is both a source of division between men and women and a site to orchestrate their reconciliation. As for the novels’ notorious depictions of bondage, discipline, and sadomasochism, Illouz shows that these are as much a cultural fantasy as a sexual one, serving as a guide to a happier romantic life. The Fifty Shades trilogy merges romantic fantasy with self-help guide—two of the most popular genres for female readers. Offering a provocative explanation for the success and popularity of the Fifty Shades of Grey novels, Hard-Core Romance is an insightful look at modern relationships and contemporary women’s literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBest sellersxSocial aspects. 0aErotic literaturexSocial aspects. 0aJames, E. L. -- Fifty shades of Grey.;Erotic literature -- Social aspects.;Best sellers -- Social aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aromantic literary criticism, gothic romance, gender studies, twilight fan-fiction, erotic novels, fifty shades of grey, lurid series, sexual ingenue, sex, bdsm, young entrepreneur, cultural phenomenon, womens issues, psychology, reading pleasure, men and women, sexuality, bondage, discipline, sadomasochism, dark fantasy, self-help guide, female readers, provocative, modern relationships, domination, social problems, emotional certainty.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226153551423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226153551/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2